Classic Potato Latkes

Yield: 4 portions

Ingredients

• 2 lb (900 g) russet potatoes (high starch)
• ¼ cup yellow onion, very small dice
• 1 large egg
• 2 tbsp all-purpose flour
• 1 tsp fine sea salt, plus more to finish
• ¼ tsp white pepper
• 3–4 tbsp clarified butter (preferred)
• 1–2 tbsp neutral oil (canola), as needed

⸻

Optional Restaurant Finishing (choose one direction)

• Lightly whipped crème fraîche
• Smoked salmon or trout
• Finely sliced chives
• Lemon zest, microplaned

⸻

Method

1. Potato preparation (critical control)

Peel potatoes and grate on the large holes of a box grater. Immediately transfer to a clean tea towel. Twist and squeeze aggressively until no liquid drips. This step determines crispness.
Discard liquid completely; do not reserve starch.

⸻

2. Base mixture

Transfer potatoes to a cold mixing bowl. Add onion, egg, flour, salt, and white pepper. Mix gently by hand just until evenly combined. Stop immediately. Overworking activates starch and creates density.

⸻

3. Pan setup

Heat a heavy skillet (cast iron preferred) over medium heat. Add clarified butter and a small amount of oil. Fat should shimmer quietly but not smoke.

⸻

4. Forming

Scoop approximately ⅓ cup mixture per pancake. Place into the pan and flatten gently to 10–12 cm (4–5 in) wide and about 8 mm (⅓ in) thick. Edges should remain irregular, not pressed smooth.

⸻

5. Cooking

Cook 3–4 minutes per side, pressing lightly once after placement, until deeply golden and audibly crisp. Flip once only. Adjust heat to maintain steady browning without scorching.

⸻

6. Resting

Transfer to a rack or paper towel. Season immediately with a light pinch of salt.
If holding briefly, keep uncovered in a 95 °C (200 °F) oven for no more than 10 minutes.

⸻

Target Texture

Deeply crisp exterior. Shredded interior fully cooked, tender, and not gummy. No surface oiliness.

⸻

Chef Notes (non-negotiable)

• Russets only. Waxy potatoes steam instead of crisp.
• Clarified butter provides flavour without burning; oil alone tastes flat.
• Onion quantity is restrained and aromatic, not structural.
• Moisture removal is decisive; most failures occur here.
• One flip preserves structure and crunch.
